though I d=\r\no not want to name any names. At the same time, some not-so-well- known tem=\r\nples seem to have a powerful divine presence.\n&gt; &gt; =C3=82 \n&gt; &gt; I was very im=\r\npressed with the=C3=82 Krishna temple in Mayapur (ISKCON head office is the=\r\nre), Girnar hills in Gujarat and Arunachalam hills in Tiruvannamalai (Raman=\r\na Maharshi&#39;s place). There is a tremendous amount of spiritual energy in th=\r\nose places. There are several temples where the idol is practically alive. =\r\nFor example, even 123 years after Ramakrishna Paramahamsa left, the Kaali i=\r\ndol at Dakshineshwar is &quot;alive&quot;. I did not get the same impression at the f=\r\namous Kalighat temple which is also in Calcutta.\n&gt; &gt; =C3=82 \n&gt; &gt; There was =\r\none small temple in Tamil Nadu that I was taken to by a priest who took me =\r\nto visit about 30 temples all over Tamil Nadu before we did the Shata Chand=\r\ni homam in Chennai in 2006. I never heard of that temple before and it seem=\r\ned like a small temple. The name of the=C3=82 form of the divine Mother=C3=\r\n=82 present there was a Tamil language name and I did not understand it. I =\r\ndo not even remember the name now. But, when I closed my eyes and started m=\r\neditating with my mantra in front of the idol, I was dazzled by a vision of=\r\n a very fierce goddess whose face was emiting rays like Sun. I felt that th=\r\nere was a powerful presence there. Unfortunately, I do not remember the nam=\r\ne of the place or the goddess, but it is a temple without roof over the god=\r\ndess. They tried to put a roof over the goddess a few times, but the roof c=\r\name down in a fire accident each time and they finally decided that the god=\r\ndess likes open air and no roof. Though we spent only 5 min and\n left\n&gt; &gt;  =\r\nin a hurry, I was very pleased with that temple. Someone from Tamil Nadu pr=\r\nobably knows the name of the temple and goddess.\n&gt; &gt; =C3=82 \n&gt; &gt; Like this,=\r\n I